31/07/2007
ANKARA, Turkey -- Turkish Chief of Staff General Yasar Buyukanit reiterated on Monday (July 30th) that the army wants the next president of the country to be committed to the basic character of the secular republic. 
In April, Buyukanit said the president should be committed to secular values. 
Buyukanit's comments on Monday were the first since the Justice and Development Party (AKP), which has roots in political Islam, won the elections on July 22nd.
Also on Monday, Turkey's election board announced the final results of the vote. 
The AKP will take 341 of the 550 seats, and the Republican People's Party gets 112. 
The far right Nationalist Movement Party has 70 seats, while independents won 26 seats, including 22 by candidates associated with the pro-Kurdish Democratic Society Party. 
(Reuters, CNN, AFP, CNN Turk, Anadolu news agency, Focus, The Washington Post - 30/07/07)
